 Indian culture onto the Manhattan and Queens landscapes. She considers festivals and media, food and dress, religious activities of followers of different faiths, work and class, gender and generational differences, and the emergence of a variety of associations.Khandelwal analyzes how this growing ethnic community has gradually become "more Indian," with a stronger religious focus, larger family networks, and increasingly traditional marriage patterns. She discusses as well the ways in which the American experience has altered the lives of her subjects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aAsian AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxEthnic identity. 0aAsian AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditions. 0aEast Indian AmericansxCultural assimilationzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aEast Indian AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxEthnic identity. 0aEast Indian AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditions. 0aImmigrantszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditions. 4aAsian Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501722028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501722028.jpg  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA